tract\":\"A blanket is a piece of soft cloth large enough either to cover or to enfold a great portion of the user's body. It is usually used when a person goes to sleep or is otherwise at rest. It traps radiant bodily heat that otherwise would be lost through convection, helping to keep the user warm. Many children and adults use a blanket as a comfort object.\",\"ExtractHtml\":\"<p>A <b>blanket</b> is a piece of soft cloth large enough either to cover or to enfold a great portion of the user's body. It is usually used when a person goes to sleep or is otherwise at rest. It traps radiant bodily heat that otherwise would be lost through convection, helping to keep the user warm. Many children and adults use a blanket as a comfort object.</p>\"}},{\"Key\":2,\"Value\":{\"Type\":\"standard\",\"Title\":\"Couch\",\"Displaytitle\":\"Couch\",\"Namespace\":{\"Id\":0,\"Text\":\"\"},\"WikibaseItem\":\"Q131514\",\"Titles\":{\"Canonical\":\"Couch\",\"Normalized\":\"Couch\",\"Display\":\"Couch\"},\"Pageid\":464961,\"Thumbnail\":{\"Source\":\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/2009-05-16_Main_office_lobby_at_Hampton_Forest_Apartments.jpg/320px-2009-05-16_Main_office_lobby_at_Hampton_Forest_Apartments.jpg\",\"Width\":320,\"Height\":213},\"Originalimage\":{\"Source\":\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c2/2009-05-16_Main_office_lobby_at_Hampton_Forest_Apartments.jpg\",\"Width\":3888,\"Height\":2592},\"Lang\":\"en\",\"Dir\":\"ltr\",\"Revision\":\"1003602168\",\"Tid\":\"cdfbd1a0-626a-11eb-87f8-9104523034d0\",\"Timestamp\":\"2021-01-29T19:47:19Z\",\"Description\":\"Piece of furniture for seating two or more persons in the form of a bench with armrests\",\"DescriptionSource\":\"local\",\"ContentUrls\":{\"Desktop\":{\"Page\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Couch\",\"Revisions\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Couch?action=history\",\"Edit\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Couch?action=edit\",\"Talk\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Couch\"},\"Mobile\":{\"Page\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Couch\",\"Revisions\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:History/Couch\",\"Edit\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Couch?action=edit\",\"Talk\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Couch\"}},\"Extract\":\"A couch, also known as a sofa, settee, futon, or chesterfield, is a piece of furniture for seating two or three people. It is commonly found in the form of a bench, with upholstered armrests, and often fitted with springs and tailored cushions. Although a couch is used primarily for seating, it may be used for sleeping. In homes, couches are normally put in the family room, living room, den or lounge. They are sometimes also found in non-residential settings such as hotels, lobbies of commercial offices, waiting rooms, and bars.\",\"ExtractHtml\":\"<p>A <b>couch</b>, also known as a <b>sofa</b>, <b>settee</b>, <b>futon</b>, or <b>chesterfield</b>, is a piece of furniture for seating two or three people. It is commonly found in the form of a bench, with upholstered armrests, and often fitted with springs and tailored cushions. Although a couch is used primarily for seating, it may be used for sleeping. In homes, couches are normally put in the family room, living room, den or lounge. They are sometimes also found in non-residential settings such as hotels, lobbies of commercial offices, waiting rooms, and bars.</p>\"}},{\"Key\":3,\"Value\":{\"Type\":\"standard\",\"Title\":\"Door\",\"Displaytitle\":\"Door\",\"Namespace\":{\"Id\":0,\"Text\":\"\"},\"WikibaseItem\":\"Q36794\",\"Titles\":{\"Canonical\":\"Door\",\"Normalized\":\"Door\",\"Display\":\"Door\"},\"Pageid\":8637,\"Thumbnail\":{\"Source\":\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/1_bis_place_de_l%27Alma_%28Paris%29.jpg/254px-1_bis_place_de_l%27Alma_%28Paris%29.jpg\",\"Width\":254,\"Height\":320},\"Originalimage\":{\"Source\":\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c3/1_bis_place_de_l%27Alma_%28Paris%29.jpg\",\"Width\":2846,\"Height\":3582},\"Lang\":\"en\",\"Dir\":\"ltr\",\"Revision\":\"1001605155\",\"Tid\":\"0f37e540-5b1e-11eb-ad64-d54ddd43ebbc\",\"Timestamp\":\"2021-01-20T12:50:17Z\",\"Description\":\"Movable barrier that allows ingress and egress\",\"DescriptionSource\":\"local\",\"ContentUrls\":{\"Desktop\":{\"Page\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Door\",\"Revisions\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Door?action=history\",\"Edit\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Door?action=edit\",\"Talk\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Door\"},\"Mobile\":{\"Page\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Door\",\"Revisions\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:History/Door\",\"Edit\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Door?action=edit\",\"Talk\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Door\"}},\"Extract\":\"A door is a hinged or otherwise movable barrier that allows ingress into and egress from an enclosure. The created opening in the wall is a doorway or portal. A door's essential and primary purpose is to provide security by controlling access to the doorway (portal). Conventionally, it is a panel that fits into the portal of a building, room, or vehicle. Doors are generally made of a material suited to the door's task. Doors are commonly attached by hinges, but can move by other means, such as slides or counterbalancing.\",\"ExtractHtml\":\"<p>A <b>door</b> is a hinged or otherwise movable barrier that allows ingress into and egress from an enclosure. The created opening in the wall is a <i>doorway</i> or <i>portal</i>. A door's essential and primary purpose is to provide security by controlling access to the doorway (portal). Conventionally, it is a panel that fits into the portal of a building, room, or vehicle. Doors are generally made of a material suited to the door's task. Doors are commonly attached by hinges, but can move by other means, such as slides or counterbalancing.</p>\"}},{\"Key\":4,\"Value\":{\"Type\":\"standard\",\"Title\":\"Saxophone\",\"Displaytitle\":\"Saxophone\",\"Namespace\":{\"Id\":0,\"Text\":\"\"},\"WikibaseItem\":\"Q9798\",\"Titles\":{\"Canonical\":\"Saxophone\",\"Normalized\":\"Saxophone\",\"Display\":\"Saxophone\"},\"Pageid\":26795,\"Thumbnail\":{\"Source\":\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Sax_range.svg/320px-Sax_range.svg.png\",\"Width\":320,\"Height\":210},\"Originalimage\":{\"Source\":\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Sax_range.svg/356px-Sax_range.svg.png\",\"Width\":356,\"Height\":234},\"Lang\":\"en\",\"Dir\":\"ltr\",\"Revision\":\"1003398728\",\"Tid\":\"3f6ba750-61a5-11eb-b63b-dd96e9192f99\",\"Timestamp\":\"2021-01-28T20:13:00Z\",\"Description\":\"type of musical instrument of the woodwind family\",\"DescriptionSource\":\"local\",\"ContentUrls\":{\"Desktop\":{\"Page\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saxophone\",\"Revisions\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saxophone?action=history\",\"Edit\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saxophone?action=edit\",\"Talk\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Saxophone\"},\"Mobile\":{\"Page\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saxophone\",\"Revisions\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:History/Saxophone\",\"Edit\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saxophone?action=edit\",\"Talk\":\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:Saxophone\"}},\"Extract\":\"The saxophone is a family of woodwind instruments usually made of brass and played with a single-reed mouthpiece. Although most saxophones are made from brass, they are categorized as woodwind instruments, because sound is produced by an oscillating reed rather than lips vibrating in a mouthpiece cup as with the brass instrument family. As with the other woodwind instruments, the pitch of the note being played is controlled by covering holes in the body tube to control the resonant frequency of the air column by changing the effective length of the tube.\\nThe player covers or uncovers the holes by pressing keys.\",\"ExtractHtml\":\"<p>The <b>saxophone</b> is a family of woodwind instruments usually made of brass and played with a single-reed mouthpiece. Although most saxophones are made from brass, they are categorized as woodwind instruments, because sound is produced by an oscillating reed rather than lips vibrating in a mouthpiece cup as with the brass instrument family. As with the other woodwind instruments, the pitch of the note being played is controlled by covering holes in the body tube to control the resonant frequency of the air column by changing the effective length of the tube.\\nThe player covers or uncovers the holes by pressing keys.</p>\"}}";
